Decision Trees & Random Forests¶

Summary of Report¶

This section describes the workflow of the following report. In this project we are given a dataset of 2020 student loans and with the following features being known:

1) Field of study (Humanities, Business, Stem)
2) Whether the university was selective in its admissions process (0, 1)
3) Student's gender (male vs. female)
4) Loan amount
5) Graduation Year
6) Whether loan defaulted or not (response variable)

Objective¶

Given this dataset we will play with decision tree and random forests classifiers to try to predict whether a loan will default in the future.

Comments on final results¶

Tree classifier
We begin by fitting a complete tree to the training dataset. The resulting tree is too big and clearly overfits the training set (visual inspection included) as anticipated. It achieves an accuracy of 80% on the test set. We proceed with tuning the tree classifier in hopes of reducing overfitting and achieving a higher accuracy on the test set. To this aim, we are using two tuning parameters, max_depth and ccp_alhpa (cost-complexity-pruning). These two methods are quite different and result in trees with different depths. However, both (optimised) trees achieve an accuracy of 86% on the test set. Nontheless, their confusion matrices differ in terms of precision and recall metrics with respect to default loans. In this case, each bank should choose the model that minimises the tradeoff between falsely flagging a loan that will not default in the future and not identifying a loan that will default in the upcoming years.

Finally, we evaluate whether the training-validation-test set approach or Kfold cross-validation is more suitable for this dataset. It turns out that more data would be ideal for this task. Therefore, KFold cross-validation is performed in order to choose the max_depth parameter. We re-fit a new tree which ends up achieving the same accuracy of 86%. Its confusion matrix is again different to the previous ones.

Random Forests
We proceed by fitting a random forest model to the data. We begin by finding a suitable number of estimators (trees) to be grown during the training phase. Due to the small number of features available and the limited size of the dataset we show that 20 trees are enough.The performance of the random forest model is worse compared to the single tree, achieving an accuracy of 83% on the test set. Its confusion matrix is yet again different to the ones resulting from single tree classifiers, yet, it is more balanced. That is, the precision and recall metrics are about 60% whereas there is a significant discrepancy between them in single tree models. Thus, a random forest model could prove better for the bank, despite its lower accuracy.

In the Random Forest section, we also compare the Out-of-Bag error estimation using all data as training set vs. the Test set error from the training-test set approach. We show that because of the limited amount of data available and the small number of tree estimators, the Out-of-Bag error tends to underestimate the test set error by roughly 1.5% points.

Finally, we use two methods, feature_importances_ and partial dependence plots PartialDependenceDisplay.from_estimator, to get a good idea of the importance of each feature on the information gain and influence on the predicted outcomes, respectively. Feature importance is widely used as a dimensionality reduction method, used in practice so limit the amount of features to the ones that are truly relevant for the response variable. Partial dependency plots are used to illustrate the functional relationship (linear vs. non-linear) between individual (or pairs of) features and the predicted variable.

1. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

1.1 Ιntroduction¶

Exploratory Data Analysis is a great tool for the user to get an idea of the data before deploying a ML algorithm. By visually inspecting data, the user gets to confirm and dispute some hypotheses/expectations and come up with new ones. Visualisation is mainly used for validating prior beliefs, but, perhaps more importantly, it should be used for discovering unexpected relationships too (which previously seemed counter-intuitive).

Unfortunately, for the best performing ML algorithms in terms of prediciton accuracy, it is usually very difficult to decompose the final prediction. Ensemble, methods such as Bagging Classifiers, Random Forests and Boosted Classifiers are averaging predictions coming from many weak learners (usually >100 weak learners) and thus the user is unable to deconstruct and backtrack the algorithms prediction. It is quite important to get an idea first before blindly testing the algorithms predictions.

In this Section, we will go through some of my own investigatory questions that I have come up with!

1.3 Summary¶

By exploring the data, we now have a much more concrete idea of what is going on (still not the full picture).

  • It is more probable that students in humanitarian studies have major difficulties in general (irrespective of which college they attended or when they graduated) with the job market and thus exhibit higher default rates.
  • Additionally, it seems that female students have slightly default rates than male students in all three study fields.
  • Graduation Year seems to reflect the impact of the global economic recesion after 2010, but not much more than that, since default rates have started to decrease steadily after 2015. Unfortunately, no data are available after 2015 and thus this column is not really informative for future loans!

4.2.3 Classification Report Inisghts¶

Missclassification Rate

  • Accuracy at 80%, i.e., 20% of all loans were missclassified

Default Loans (=1)

  • Precision = of 58%, i.e., 42% of loans classified as default did not actually default. That means that using this classifier the bank expects that from all loans that it will flag and further examine in the future, 42% will not actually default in the following years.

  • Recall of 59%, i.e., 41% of loans classified as non-default did actually default. That means that using this classifier the bank will expect to identify 59% of all student loans that will actually turn out to default.

  • 65 loans that did not did not default, were flagged as default (False Positives - FP)
  • 69 loans that did default , were not flagged as default (False Negatives - FN)
  • 438 loans that did not default, were correctly identified (True Negative - TN)

4.3 Tuning a decision tree classifier using training and validation set¶

4.3.1 Tree max_depth parameter¶

In [402]:
X_train2, X_val, y_train2, y_val = train_test_split(X_train, y_train, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)
In [403]:
print('Size of training set:', len(X_train2))
print('Size of validation set:', len(X_val))

Size of training set: 1014
Size of validation set: 339

The complete tree that was trained in the previous section has a depth of 33. Thus, there is no point in searching for depth>33.

In [404]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
In [405]:
validation_accuracy = [] # list of accuracy scores on validation set
training_accuracy = [] # list of accuracy scores on training set

full_depth = dtree.get_depth()

for depth in range(1,full_depth):
    
    dtree_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = depth)
    
    dtree_tuned.fit(X_train2,y_train2)
    
    predictions_tuned_val = dtree_tuned.predict(X_val)
    predictions_tuned_train = dtree_tuned.predict(X_train2)
    
    validation_accuracy.append(accuracy_score(y_val,predictions_tuned_val))
    training_accuracy.append(accuracy_score(y_train2,predictions_tuned_train))

4.3.2 Plot Validation vs Training Accuracy¶

In [406]:
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (10,6)

plt.plot(range(1,full_depth), validation_accuracy, color='red')
plt.plot(range(1,full_depth), training_accuracy, color='green')
plt.legend(['Validation accuracy', 'Training Accuracy'])
plt.xlabel('Tree depth')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('Validation accuracy vs. Tree depth')
Out[406]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Validation accuracy vs. Tree depth')

Training Accuracy
As far as training accuracy is concerend, it increases monotonically with tree_depth as expected. It actually reaches 100% at depth = 33. This seems that every training data point has been correctly identified at this stage. Trees area highly variant/flexible models due to the high number of splits they can execute. That means that they have the ability to fit the training data too well, picking up trends that are particular to this dataset, but not representative of the population. In this case they seem to overfit the training set and thus perform worse on the test set. This is because the resulting tree might be too complex.

Validation Accuracy We can clearly see that the best accuracy on the validaton set is achieved for a small tree depth around 1-3. The accuracy is around 84%, which is a good indication that it will perform on the test set as well. After that depth level, it seems that the tree has already started overfitting the dataset

4.5 Tuning a tree using cost complexity pruning¶

Reference1
Reference2

Get alpha values and the weighted impurities of leaf nodes resulting from pruning the tree using the respective alhpa value

In [415]:
dtree_ccp = DecisionTreeClassifier()
path = dtree_ccp.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train2, y_train2)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

For all alpha values obtained in the previous step, fit a new tree and append it to a list of trees called trees.

In [416]:
trees = []

for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    tree_ccp = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    tree_ccp.fit(X_train2, y_train2)
    trees.append(tree_ccp)

trees = trees[:-1]
ccp_alphas = ccp_alphas[:-1]

Evaluate train and validation accuracy for every tree based and plot them

It seems that with the given dataset, the learning rate continues to improve as the size of the training set increases. This serves as clear indication for:

  1. We would ideally gather more data on this topic
  2. We should probably use cross-validation instead of a training-validation-test set approach
  3. For KFold cross validation we should probably use K=5 (get at least 1000 data points in each fold)

4.6.2 KFold cross validation¶

In [429]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

kf = KFold(n_splits=5, random_state=10, shuffle=True)
kf.get_n_splits(X)
Out[429]:
5
In [430]:
opt_depths = []

for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X):
    
    X_train, X_test = X.loc[train_index,:], X.loc[test_index,:] 
    Y_train, Y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    
    accuracy_test   = []
    
    for depth in range(1,21):
        
        tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=depth)
        tree.fit(X_train, Y_train)
        preds_train = tree.predict(X_train)
        preds_val = tree.predict(X_test)
        accuracy_test.append(accuracy_score(Y_test, preds_val)*100)
    
    opt_depth = np.argmax(np.array(accuracy_test))
    opt_depths.append([opt_depth+1, accuracy_test[opt_depth]])
    
depths = [i[0] for i in opt_depths]

plt.hist(depths)

4.7 Conlusion on single Decision Tree Classifier¶

So far we tried three different methods of tuning the decision tree. In particular we tuned using:

  1. max_depth with training-validation set
  2. cost-complexity tuning with trainin-validation set
  3. max_depth with KFold cross validation

Every time that we fitted the optimal tree according to each methodology, we got a different tree depth and at the end the same missclassification accuracy. Precision and Recall metrics were not identical, meaning that the bank could choose which classifier it should use based on the respective costs of failing to identify a loan that will turn out to default, and spending resources on a falsely identified default-prone loan.

In any case, the bank had previously no way of identifying a default-prone loan, as the majority of them were non-defaults. The company should compare the total cost of no-action to the total expected cost of each of these methodologies, and choose the less costly option before deploying the ML method.

All trees are relatively shallow, that means that it is easy to understand and interpret them, which is extremely useful and significant for banks, as they should be able to justify their actions to clients (e.g., not accepting a loan)

5.2 Fitting a Random Forest model¶

5.2.1 Use all data and Out of bag error¶

In [442]:
rf_fs = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=20, 
                            bootstrap = True,
                            max_features='sqrt',
                            oob_score = True,
                            random_state=1)

rf_fs.fit(X,y)
Out[442]:
RandomForestClassifier(max_features='sqrt', n_estimators=20, oob_score=True,
                       random_state=1)

The random forest above is going to build 100 trees by re-sampling the initial dataset (X) using Boostrap. In addition to that, in each split of each tree, only $\sqrt{4}=2$ features will be considered. Moreover, oob_score is enabled. This parameter will be explained in more detail in the following section. Finally, by setting a random_state, we are fixing the randomness involved in the bootstrap procedure as well as the subset of features considered in each tree and each split

oob (out of bag error)

We now estimate the accuracy of the model (on unseen data) using out of bag errors seen during the training of the algorithm. The reasoning behind this feature is that each tree is tested on the subset of the data that were not selected during boostraping for its training data set. Then the out of bag error is calculated as the average test error of all trees (in this ase 100)

In [443]:
rf_fs.oob_score_
Out[443]:
0.8361386138613861

The Random Forest algorithm performs slightly worse than the single tree based on this score

5.2.2 Use training-test set approach¶

Training-Test set error

In [444]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=42)

rf_nfs = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, 
                            bootstrap = True,
                            max_features='sqrt',
                            oob_score = False,
                            random_state=1)

rf_nfs.fit(X_train,y_train)
rf_nfs.score(X_test,y_test)
Out[444]:
0.8290854572713643

We see that there is some discrepancy between the oob score and the training-test set misclassificaton error. In particular, it seems that the oob score underestimates the expected misclassification error rate on unseen data. Perhaps, as the number of estimators increases oob converges towards the training test error rate. It shall be noted that these two errors are associated with the fixed random_state defined in the classifier. For a different random_state, we will get different estimates, but they should not vary significantly.

5.3 Feature Importance¶

When using the Random Forests model, we can estimate the importance of each feature by using the feature_importances_ attribute of the fitted model. Feature importance is the total (considering all trees) Gini/Entropy reduction brought about by a feature divided by the maximum total reduction brought about by all features

In [448]:
importances = rf_nfs.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

col_names = list(X.columns)

print("Feature ranking:")
for f in range(len(indices)):
    print("%d. %s (%f)" % (f + 1, col_names[indices[f]], importances[indices[f]]))
